      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Sir— ¶  ¶  ¶ Having but recently returned from the south-eastern frontiers of Gipps Land, ¶ Vic. ¶  ¶ it was not until this day that my attention was directed to a letter, published in The Herald on ¶...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">60.10.19</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Editor of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Herald</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Herald</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Melbourne), 20 October 1860, p.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>5 (B60.10.02).<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>In republishing M's letter,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">South Australian register</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">25 October</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>1860</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, p. 3</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(B60.10.03</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">)</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">,</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">wrote: 'Dr. Mueller, it will be seen, even without knowing the particulars of Mr. Stuart's journey, has taken up the cudgels in his defence.'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Sir—<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Having but recently returned from the south-eastern frontiers of Gipps Land,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Vic.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>it was not until this day that my attention was directed to a letter, published in The Herald on<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>29th Sept.,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Herald</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Melbourne), 29 September 1860,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">p. 5, under the heading ‘Mr. Stuart’s Exploration’, carried a letter signed ‘R. D.’ that argued that it would have been ‘a physical impossibility’ for Stuart to have reached a position as far north as he claimed, and then to have returned to the settled districts, in the time available. The letter also disparaged the small size of Stuart’s party, insinuating that such a small group could not possibly have achieved what was claimed.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to which a strong feeling for justice prompts me to offer a few remarks in reply.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Although I am not aware of the exact time when Mr. Stuart actually commenced the harassing task,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>so gloriously achieved,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of crossing the continent, I am under the impression,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that he awaited on Chambers's Creek<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>SA.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the commencement of the cool season, as the most favourable for traversing the interior. If Mr. Stuart struck out on his noble path in the beginning of April, he would have had sufficient time available to reach the position which he assigns to the most northern point gained in his exploration, and thence to return to the outskirt settlements of South Australia, travelling at the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>ratio in which Mr. Gregory performed his journey from the lower Victoria River to Moreton Bay.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. during the final stage of the North Australian Exploring Expedition, 1855-6.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>We are well aware that Mr. Stuart must have expended considerable time in his repeated attempts to connect his survey with that of Mt Gregory towards Central Australia.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>'The expedition had actually penetrated a hundred miles further north … than Gregory, in his North Australian Expedition, to the south, effecting for all practical purposes the crossing of the Continent' (Threadgill<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">(</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">1922</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">)</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, p. 53). For Stuart's diary see<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Adelaide</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">observer</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, 15 December 1860, pp 3S-4S.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>Yet it must also not be forgotten, when comparing the relative lengths of Mr. Gregory's and Mr. Stuart's tracks, that the former gentleman's journey involved also many delays in fruitless endeavours to adopt with safety a less circuitous course than that excellent leader was able to take.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Nor ought we, in estimating the possible celerity of travelling in the interior, be unmindful that the smallest party, if favoured by circumstances, is likely to make the most rapid progress— indeed, the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>safety of the party often<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>depends on such rapid strides as to render the collecting of the scattered tribes of the nomades impossible around them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>That a strong party is not absolutely necessary for traversing the Australian interior,—to however much danger a few isolated travellers may be exposed— is fully demonstrated by facts which I scarcely need here record. Captain Sturt had but a solitary companion<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">alon</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">e</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the main lines of his last journey. Eyre toiled for hundreds of miles alone,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">reconnoitre</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">ing</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the barren solitudes at Lake Torrens,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>SA.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in advance of his party, and rounded finally the Great Bight,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>accompanied by but one native. Mr. Augustus Gregory performed his most difficult journeys<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>even amongst hordes of hostile natives but very few companions, and but three out of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>his<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>party were his followers to Termination<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Lake.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Now Lake Gregory, WA, the furthest point inland reached during the North Australian Exploring Expedition.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The graphic account of some of the incidents given lately of Mr Stuart's journey, accord well with what we experienced in Northern Australia. The signal columns of smoke, which call the black warriors together against what they always consider invaders, arose frequently around us when traversing the country around the Gulf of Carpentaria, and it was within 200 miles of the spot where Mr. Stuart encountered the fiery attacks of the natives,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that Mr. Gregory's party narrowly escaped destruction by a nightly attack of the natives.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the early morning of 5 September 1856, during the North Australian Exploring Expedition, Gregory’s party was attacked by a band of Aborigines while crossing the Leichhardt River near the Gulf of Carpentaria.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The very fact that a traveller has been able to retrace his steps over a wide tract<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of unexplored country,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is sufficient evidence that his positions must have been carefully ascertained, and that his charts must have been constructed with a considerable amount of exactness, landmarks being but too often wanting for guidance, and the lives of the travellers too frequently depending on solitary waterholes. Mr. J. Macdouall Stuart's well-known name as an experienced surveyor is, moreover, a further guarantee of the exactness of the charts,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>with which he will enrich Australian geography.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is a source of deep regret,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that whilst every true friend of progress of Australian discovery,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>hailed Mr. Stuart's triumphant return with feelings of unmingled delight, that he and the generous man,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>who<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>largely if not entirely<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>was actuated by a rare cosmopolitan disinterestedness in fostering this noble enterprise, should have disturbed the pure joy of their successes. Mr. James Chambers,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of Adelaide, has set our patricians a rare example. Now in gratitude to the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>prolific gifts of youthful Australia,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>a tribute should be paid on her altar. Although the late enterprises of Stuart have involved the expenditure of thousands, yet the magnanimity of their promoter is by no means exhausted, and Mr. Stuart will again rely, to a great extent, on his former private support, well seconded by the South Australian Government.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The SA<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">G</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">overnment voted £2,500 to provide an escort for Stuart on his next journey, still supported by James Chambers, who effectively vetoed the appointment of a scientific officer (Threadgold<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">(</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">1922</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">)</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, pp. 53-60).</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Whilst to John Macdouall Stuart the palm of merit is due,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of having virtually crossed the continent from north to south, inasmuch as even now the enterprise of the squatters would enable them to bring their herds on a short route from Lake Torrens to the fertile pastures of Amheim's Land, whenever that fine tract of Australia becomes colonized, the main goal of geographical discoveries lies now in the western part of the continent.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Thence we see Major Warburton with his slender party,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bend now courageously his path. Thence, to a wide field for decennial exertions we trust the Victorian expedition<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Burke<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">&amp;</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Wills expedition, then in the field.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>will strike out for glorious achievements, adopting Columbus's call — ' To the westward.'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">I remain, Mr. Editor, most regardfully yours,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Mueller.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne Botanical and Zoological Garden,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>19th<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>October, 1860.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
